<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,222,571]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<bibRefCitation author="Fujiyama" box="[199,391,402,427]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Fujiyama, I. (1983) A Pleistocene nymphalid butterfly from Shiobara, Japan. Bulletin of the National Science Museum, Tokyo (C), 9, 121 - 128." type="journal article" year="1983">Fujiyama (1983)</bibRefCitation>
reported on finding of the proximal half of a left forewing of which the basal part was missing. The open forewing cell and the branching off of the median veins are quite visible, as well as white patches and streaks. Venation and wing design agree completely with those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1037,1230,476,499]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Hestina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[1037,1230,476,499]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Hestina japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an extant species widely distributed in Japan, Korea, China and Taiwan. If this wing fragment had been found in a spider web, nobody would have doubted its identity.
</paragraph>
